<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEBATE OVER RAIL LINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In reading your article regarding transit ("Rail Lines Offered for Sale Are 
Focus of Transit Debate," by Ronald Taylor, Metro, July 18), I couldn't help 
but notice the comments of Westwood resident Steve Kunin. 
</P>
<P>
If he doesn't believe we should use existing rights of way for rail 
transportation, what does he propose we do about the congestion on our 
freeways, surface streets and neighborhoods? We got rid of the old rail system 
to, among other things, build more freeways and that "solution" has run its 
course. 
</P>
<P>
In stating that rail transit isn't needed, he is ignoring the cheapest, most 
convenient alternative to a congestion problem the rest of us believe exists. 
</P>
<P>
Steve, maybe the next time you are stuck in traffic along Santa Monica 
Boulevard Westwood you could look down between the medians that separate the 
street. It may be hard to believe but at one time those rails carried scores of 
passengers from the Eastside to the Westside and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
If the Los Angeles County Transportation Commission is allowed to purchase 
these rights of way, maybe we can someday ride that line and others like it 
again. 
</P>
<P>
NICK SANTANGELO 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
