</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
425 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE GALLERIES: WILSHIRE CENTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CATHY CURTIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1903, when photography was still knocking timidly on the imposing front door 
of art, Alfred Stieglitz began publishing Camera Work. In its 14-year lifespan, 
the quarterly magazine would make a big case for the aesthetic possibilities of 
the medium, aided by the most scrupulous printing methods available and 
far-ranging essays on art and photography. 
</P>
<P>
The images in the journal, displayed individually in this exhibit, are 
hand-pulled photogravures usually made from the original negatives and printed 
on Japanese tissue to retain the delicate gradation of tone. Robert Demachy -- 
whose 1904 photograph, "Speed," shows a roadster disappearing down a soft gray 
road lined with trees -- noted wryly that "For the initiated or perhaps for the 
insane . . . there is a most exquisite pleasure in the contemplation of fine 
shades" of black "independently of form." 
</P>
<P>
Form in the works on view generally takes on a dreamy aura, bearing out the 
Photo-Secession group's belief that a photograph ought to possess the evident 
artistry of a painting rather than utilitarian sharp focus. (Stieglitz's views 
on this matter changed radically by 1917, when he was a champion of "straight" 
photography, but the show emphasizes Camera Work's early years.) 
</P>
<P>
Karl Struss' "The Landing Place" peers down at a gentle summer scene: a 
graceful stone balustrade and shady tree overlooking a lake with a lazy rowboat 
and barge. In "Ploughing," Stieglitz finds a glorious palette of grays in the 
sky above a farmer and the black and white flanks of his horses. Theodore 
Hofmeister's "Dachau" brings today's viewer up short with a placid view of 
white houses and tall trees. (The photograph predates by 29 years the 
concentration camp established on the outskirts of this picturesque German 
town.) 
</P>
<P>
Along with nature, young women were favorite subjects. Stieglitz's "Miss S.R." 
introduces a moodily attractive femme fatale in a pert hat. As an emblem of 
"Spring," he choose a toddler in a bonnet and flaring coat, planted in profile 
on the grassy meadow like a giant flower. In George H. Seeley's "The White 
Screen," a slender woman in a long gown and flowing shoulder wrap is bathed in 
light-dappled shadow. 
</P>
<P>
Other Camera Work photographers whose work is sampled here include Baron Adolf 
de Meyer, a specialist in luminous portraits and still lifes, and the 
mid-19th-Century duo of David Octavius Hill and Robert Adamson, revered by 
members of Photo-Secession as early masters of the photographic portrait. 
(Tobey C. Moss, 7321 Beverly Blvd., to Aug. 12.) CATHY CURTIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Robert Demachy's "Speed" in Camera Work show at Moss Gallery. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Art Review 
</P>
