<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Canadians began returning home to salvage what remains from fires that 
destroyed 3.7 million acres of forest in three central provinces. Some 
roadblocks in Manitoba were lifted, and a group from the Cross Lake Indian 
Reserve returned to their homes a few hours later. They were among the 27,000 
people forced from their homes by the fires in northern Manitoba, Saskatchewan 
and Ontario. No injuries or deaths were reported. Scattered rain and cooler 
temperatures helped bring some fires under control, but hundreds of others were 
still burning. 
</P>
