<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Senate Judiciary Committee postponed until next week a vote on whether 
William Lucas should head the Justice Department's civil rights agency so that 
a key member, Sen. Howell Heflin (D-Ala.), could study new material. Heflin, 
considered a pivotal vote, did not say what the new material was, and committee 
workers involved with the nomination declined to comment. Republican members 
tried to force a vote so that the nomination could be brought to the full 
Senate before Congress' Aug. 5 recess but Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. (D-Del.), 
chairman of the committee, rescheduled a vote for Tuesday. Lucas, 61, has met 
opposition from some civil rights groups and liberal lawmakers who question his 
qualifications and his knowledge of recent Supreme Court decisions they 
consider anti-civil rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
