</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MIAMI 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Soviet Navy vessel picked up three Cuban refugees adrift in an inner-tube 
raft off the Florida coast today and helped them seek political asylum in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
The Soviets lowered a life raft into the water, picked up the refugees, then 
radioed the U.S. Coast Guard and asked them to pick up the Cubans, the Coast 
Guard said. 
</P>
<P>
The refugees said they left from Santa Cruz, Cuba, last Saturday aboard a 
12-foot boat that later capsized and sank. The three were taken to Jackson 
Memorial Hospital, where they were in stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
A Coast Guard spokesman said Soviet crewmen had questioned the Cubans and were 
aware the Cubans were fleeing the Communist island. 
</P>
